Briefly, an 83 years old female with bullous pemphigoid, diabetes type 2, dyslipidemia, CKD, DVT/PE (was on Coumadin, recently stopped due to large right retroperitoneal hematoma), hypothyroidism, nephrolithiasis, OSA, recently discharged from MGH (3/10 - 3/19/20) after admitted for retroperitoneal hematoma discharged on 3/19/2020 now presented on 4/18/2020 for evaluation of altered mental status, abdominal pain and diarrhea found to have UTI with sepsis, AKI on CKD with creatinine as high as 6.1 on admission.
# Sepsis secondary to UTI
- Work-up reviewed so far. Urine culture positive for Streptococcus, final c/s pending.
- Continue empiric antibiotics including IV vancomycin, cefepime and metronidazole pending final cultures
- Currently hemodynamically stable, and not requiring vasopressors.
- Most recent lactate actually at 2.8 and remained stable. Continue to monitor lactic acid, urine output, mental status.
- Ordered 500 cc LR bolus due to decreasing urine output.
- Discussed with patient's daughter who is currently unable to make a decision about changing the CODE STATUS, and will get back to us after discussing with additional family members.
- If patient becomes hypotensive to the point where she needs vasopressor support, would reach the daughter again to reevaluate goals of care.
- Palliative care consultation has also been requested.
# Oliguric AKI on CKD, likely from ATN secondary to sepsis:
- Creatinine slowly downtrending with most recently 0.47 this a.m. however urine output is decreasing.
- Followed by nephrologist Dr.Ali. Currently urgent indication for dialysis
- Again, given her overall comorbidities, advanced age, and poor quality of life, would not recommend dialysis.
# Altered level of consciousness, from metabolic encephalopathy secondary UTI and sepsis
- Continue treatment of underlying condition with IV antibiotics and IV fluids.
- No gross focal deficits. No need for CT head without contrast at this time.
# Large subcapsular/perinephric hematoma of the right kidney:
- CT showed right retroperitoneal hematoma associated with the right kidney 13.7 x 15.1 x 14.9 cm angiomyolipoma.
- Continue monitor H&H and transfuse for hemoglobin less than 7.0.
- Evaluated by urology, Dr. Freedman. Currently no plan for any intervention. Continue conservative management with IV antibiotics.
# Possible colitis on CT abdomen/pelvis:
- CT abdomen/pelvis shows development of large volume of retained rectal stool with evidence for impaction. Mild rectal wall thickening and stranding suggests early stercoral colitis.
- Patient was disimpacted yesterday. Continue with clear liquids and bowel regimen. Passing flatus.
- Continue IV antibiotics including IV Flagyl. Follow-up on final stool studies including ova and parasites.
# History of hypertension:
- Holding antihypertensives in the setting of sepsis.
# History of DVT/PE:
- Anticoagulation on hold due to recent perinephric hematoma
# Diabetes type 2:
- Fairly controlled. Continue with Accu-Cheks and low-dose sliding scale insulin.
# Hypothyroidism:
- Continue levothyroxine per home regimen
# FEN: Clear liquids advance as tolerated
# Glucose: fairly controlled. C/w SSI. BG goal 120-160
# Prophylaxis: SCDs for DVT prophylaxis, PPI for stress ulcer prophylaxis
# Lines/tubes: PIV, Foley
# CODE STATUS: Full code
# Disposition: Remains in ICU

# AKI on CKD:In view of her history likely prerenal causes which led to hypotension and now she most likely has ATN.Sepsis might be contributing as well.Postobstructive ruled out with a CT scan of the abdomen.CKD likely due to DM and HTN.Her baseline creatinine is around 1.3 with an EGFR of around 40. On this admission, she was found to have an acute kidney injury with a creatinine of 6.15 and an EGFR of 8.She has been given 3.5 L of fluids since admission and her urine output has been 700 cc in the last 24 hours.Her creatinine has improved marginally to 5.68 after IV fluid resuscitation.FeNa is 1.35% and FeUrea is 19%
# Hypotension.On D5N0.45NS.
#Hyperkalemia: Likely due to AKI and constipation.Now potassium has improved from 5.9 to 5.1 after IVF
# Anion gap metabolic acidosis: AG of 16 on admission.Likely due to AKI on CKD.
# Hyperphosphatemia: likely due to AKI.
# Constipation: has been disimpacted
# Altered mental status
# Retroperitoneal hematoma: Urology have been consulted and recommend conservative management.
Recommendations
-Continue IVF
-No indication for dialysis at the moment
–Strict I's and O's
–Monitor BMP, magnesium and phosphorus
–Daily weights
–Avoid nephrotoxins
-Avoid episodes of hypotension
-Rest of the management per primary team
Thank you for consulting capital nephrology. We will continue to follow the patient.

After discussion/request by Dr Ghaemmaghami, I reviewed her Hospital records, labs, and Radiol Images from last admission in march, and today's.
There has been some resolution of Retroperitneal Hematoma in the interim (comparing CT 3/11 to 4/18), but the degree of mass effect is still pronounced, pushing the nonhydronephrotic R kidney anteriorly. The left kidney appears unchanged, no hydro, normal parenchyma, but there is an unchanged mixed density exophytic lateral cyst, probably proteinaceous.
It appears she had a spontaneous retroperitneal bleed from her right kidney, when her INR was >4.
The present appearance of her kidneys is essentially unchanged from last admission (and there appears to be no obstruction), so there is nothing anatamical to account for the rise in Creat to 6.1.
This acute change would appear to be more due to sepsis, and renal causes, not post renal. - so it does not appear that any Urological interventions would help at present for the Azotemia.
One of the underlying not yet diagnosed issues is if there is any underlying pathology of the Right kidney to account for the large hematoma/bleed in the first place.
Diff dx includes: Renal cell Ca vs. Angiomyolipoma (benign vascular tumor) , vs. much less frequently some underlying other vascular abnormality.
The non contrast CT does not give enough detail to differentiate these.
Perhaps an abd. MRI would give better information, but even so that would be a non contrast study given her present renal functioning.
And unless the patient was becoming hemodynamically unstable due to blood loss, no urgent intervention is needed for any of the above diagnoses.
It is possible that she could have an infected perirenal hematoma, but unless there was an enlarging mixed density mass, i would recommend covering with antibiotic tx, and see how she does with supportive care. If her sepsis picture worsens, one could get IR opinion on placing a possible perc drain (if there was a specific region to target). It would be unusual for a lower urinary tract infection (in bladder) to lead to a pyelo in the abscence of obstruction or anatomic abn.; but hematologic spread could potentially infect a hematoma.
Obviously Nephrology input is necessary; if the patient & family want aggressive care, then temporary Dialysis may be necessary to see how well she can recover. (Even at discharge in March her renal insufficiency was not back at baseline.)
ID consult may also be of assistance.
So serial imaging with US or CT for now would be helpful to see if any changes noted suggestive of abscess transformation.
For now I can follow her course with you.
Call me if any acute issues (209-768-1958)
Thank you for this interesting consult.

paragraph.content: Patient Education
Hospice

text.paragraph:
Hospice
Hospice is a service that is designed to provide people who are terminally ill and their families with medical, spiritual, and psychological support. Its aim is to improve your quality of life by keeping you as comfortable as possible in the final stages of life.
Who will be my providers when I begin hospice care?
Hospice teams often include:
• A nurse.
• A doctor. The hospice doctor will be available for your care, but you can include your regular doctor or nurse practitioner.
• A social worker.
• A counselor.
• A religious leader (such as a chaplain).
• A dietitian.
• Therapists.
• Trained volunteers who can help with care.
What services does hospice provide?
Hospice services can vary depending on the center or organization. Generally, they include:
• Ways to keep you comfortable, such as:
? Providing care in your home or in a home-like setting.
? Working with your family and friends to help meet your needs.
? Allowing you to enjoy the support of loved ones by receiving much of your basic care from family and friends.
• Pain relief and symptom management. The staff will supply all necessary medicines and equipment so that you can stay comfortable and alert enough to enjoy the company of your friends and family.
• Visits or care from a nurse and doctor. This may include 24-hour on-call services.
• Companionship when you are alone.
• Allowing you and your family to rest. Hospice staff may do light housekeeping, prepare meals, and run errands.
• Counseling. They will make sure your emotional, spiritual, and social needs are being met, as well as those needs of your family members.
• Spiritual care. This will be individualized to meet your needs and your family's needs. It may involve:
? Helping you and your family understand the dying process.
? Helping you say goodbye to your family and friends.
? Performing a specific religious ceremony or ritual.
• Massage.
• Nutrition therapy.
• Physical and occupational therapy.
• Short-term inpatient care, if something cannot be managed in the home.
• Art or music therapy.
• Bereavement support for grieving family members.
When should hospice care begin?
Most people who use hospice are believed to have less than 6 months to live.
• Your family and health care providers can help you decide when hospice services should begin.
• If you live longer than 6 months but your condition does not improve, your doctor may be able to approve you for continued hospice care.
• If your condition improves, you may discontinue the program.
What should I consider before selecting a program?
Most hospice programs are run by nonprofit, independent organizations. Some are affiliated with hospitals, nursing homes, or home health care agencies. Hospice programs can take place in your home or at a hospice center, hospital, or skilled nursing facility. When choosing a hospice program, ask the following questions:
• What services are available to me?
• What services will be offered to my loved ones?
• How involved will my loved ones be?
• How involved will my health care provider be?
• Who makes up the hospice care team? How are they trained or screened?
• How will my pain and symptoms be managed?
• If my circumstances change, can the services be provided in a different setting, such as my home or in the hospital?
• Is the program reviewed and licensed by the state or certified in some other way?
• What does it cost? Is it covered by insurance?
• If I choose a hospice center or nursing home, where is the hospice center located? Is it convenient for family and friends?
• If I choose a hospice center or nursing home, can my family and friends visit any time?
• Will you provide emotional and spiritual support?
• Who can my family call with questions?
Where can I learn more about hospice?
You can learn about existing hospice programs in your area from your health care providers. You can also read more about hospice online. The websites of the following organizations have helpful information:
• National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization (NHPCO): www.nhpco.org
• National Association for Home Care & Hospice (NAHC): www.nahc.org
• Hospice Foundation of America (HFA): www.hospicefoundation.org
• American Cancer Society (ACS): www.cancer.org
• Hospice Net: www.hospicenet.org
• Visiting Nurse Associations of America (VNAA): www.vnaa.org
You may also find more information by contacting the following agencies:
• A local agency on aging.
• Your local United Way chapter.
• Your state's department of health or social services.
Summary
• Hospice is a service that is designed to provide people who are terminally ill and their families with medical, spiritual, and psychological support.
• Hospice aims to improve your quality of life by keeping you as comfortable as possible in the final stages of life.
• Hospice teams often include a doctor, nurse, social worker, counselor, religious leader,dietitian, therapists, and volunteers.
• Hospice care generally includes medicine for symptom management, visits from doctors and nurses, physical and occupational therapy, nutrition counseling, spiritual and emotional counseling, caregiver support, and bereavement support for grieving family members.
• Hospice programs can take place in your home or at a hospice center, hospital, or skilled nursing facility.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
